ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Despite an enthusiastic reception to the news, Louis Vuitton=E2=80=99s =
entr=C3=A9e into makeup came
as a surprise to most. =E2=80=9CThey always said they would never do it,=E2=
=80=9D said a person with knowledge of LVMH=E2=80=99s beauty business. =E2=
=80=9CWithin the company, it was discussed that makeup always ends up in th=
e gray market and is brand dilutive=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and Louis Vuitton woul=
d never take that risk.=E2=80=9D According to insiders, the brand wasn=E2=
=80=99t expected to dabble in beauty categories outside of fragrance, and t=
hen only as long as it was =E2=80=9Cvery contained=E2=80=9D in its own stor=
es to avoid brand dilution, naturally.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Mean=
while, it=E2=80=99s increasingly hard to stand out in makeup=E2=80=94a real=
ity that LVMH knows as well as anyone, given its ownership of Sephora. But =
Louis Vuitton=E2=80=99s desire to delve deeper into beauty is understandabl=
e: It=E2=80=99s a lucrative business with great margins and has proven rece=
ssion-resilient. So I=E2=80=99m eager to assess the initial lineup, and esp=
ecially whether the <em>packaging </em>lives up to the brand.
(McGrath told <em>Vogue </em>that there will be =E2=80=9Cdedicated small le=
ather goods=E2=80=9D designed to house La Beaut=C3=A9 products, similar to =
the $745 logo traveling cases for fragrance.) The initial lineup, which goe=
s on sale in the fall, includes 55 shades of lipstick, lip balms, and eye s=
hadow palettes, which were always the best thing about McGrath=E2=80=99s ow=
n makeup line.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>There are grounds for optimis=
m. I=E2=80=99ve heard that Louis Vuitton=E2=80=99s nearly decade-old perfum=
e line, whose 100-ml
bottles retail for $330 and are sold only in the brand=E2=80=99s 400 or so =
stores worldwide, is about a<em> $500 million</em> business. Frankly, it co=
uld be bigger. I=E2=80=99ve always felt that Louis Vuitton was leaving mone=
y on the table given the limited distribution, even as the brand has amasse=
d some nice incremental sales in the category. Of course, with leather good=
s as its core business, beauty has never been much more than a brand-enhanc=
ing side hustle for LV. The person with knowledge of LVMH=E2=80=99s
business put it more bluntly: =E2=80=9CMakeup was always below them.=E2=80=
=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
